,"type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French (Lorraine): variant of the habitational name   Delle   2 or a masculine form of a homonymous topographic name. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Spanish or Italian preposition with fused definite article <i>del</i> ‘of the’, which forms first part of surnames such as   Del Cid   and   Del Signore  , has apparently been in some instances counted as an independent surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Delle","meanings":["German: habitational name from a place so named in North Rhine-Westphalia or a topographic name (see   Dell  ).","French (Lorraine): habitational name from Delle, a place in Territoire de Belfort. Alternatively, a topographic name, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’, for someone who lived near a prominent alder tree or trees, from <i>elle</i>, a derivative of Middle High German <i>erle</i> ‘alder’."]}]},{"name":"Vasto,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Slovak and Czech (<b>Vaško</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Václav</i> (see   Vaclav  ).","Ukrainian, Rusyn, and Slovak; Croatian (mainly <b>Vaško</b>): from the personal names <i>Vasko</i>, <i>Vaško</i>, pet forms of local vernacular equivalents (e.g. Ukrainian <i>Vasyl</i>, Slovak   Vasil  ) of Greek <i>Basileios</i> ‘royal’ (see   Basil  ). Compare   Vasco   3,   Wasko  , and   Washko  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Washko","meanings":["Americanized form of Slovak, Czech, and Croatian <b>Vaško</b>, Polish <b>Waśko</b> (see   Vasko   and   Wasko  )."]},{"name":"Vaclav","meanings":["Czech and Slovak (<b>Václav</b>): from the personal name <i>Václav</i>, Old Czech <i>Vęceslav</i>, Latinized as <i>Wenceslaus</i>, from an Old Slavic name composed of the elements <i>vet'e</i> ‘more, greater’ + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’ (from <i>slava</i> ‘glory’). It was borne by a 10th-century duke of Bohemia who fought against a revival of paganism in his territory; after his death he was adopted as patron saint of Bohemia."]}]},{"name":"Bonifacio","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Bonifatius</i> ‘good fate’; borne by several early saints."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bonifacio I del Vasto, Marquis of Clavesana was born about 1140, in Cortemilia, Cuneo, Piedmont, Italy, his father, Anselme I del Vasto de Clavesane, was 42 and his mother, Anne Marie del Vento, was 17. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Hélène de Bergame. He died after 27 September 1223, in Savona, Liguria, Italy."},"et":{"Abt 1140–after 27 September 1223":"umbes 1140–pärast 27. septembrit 1223","1140–1223":"1140–1223","1145–1219":"1145–1219","1154–Female":"1154–Surnud","1170–1237":"1170–1237","1175–1233":"1175–1233","1182–1224":"1182–1224","1100–1162":"1100–1162","1125–Female":"1125–Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1162":"1162","1140":"1140","after 27 September 1223":"pärast 27. septembrit 1223","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","Abt 1140":"umbes 1140","1237":"1237","1125":"1125","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1233":"1233","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1219":"1219","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Andora,Savona,Italy":"Savona, Liguria, Itaalia","Cortemilia, Italy":"Cortemilia, Cuneo, Piemonte, Itaalia","Ceva, Cuneo, Piemonte, Italie":"Ceva, Cuneo, Piemonte, Itaalia","Clavesana, Cuneo, Piedmont, Italy":"Clavesana, Cuneo, Piemonte, Itaalia"},"fi":{"Abt 1140–after 27 September 1223":"noin 1140–27. syyskuuta 1223 jälkeen","1140–1223":"1140–1223","1145–1219":"1145–1219","1154–Female":"1154–Kuollut","1170–1237":"1170–1237","1175–1233":"1175–1233","1182–1224":"1182–1224","1100–1162":"1100–1162","1125–Female":"1125–Kuollut","about 1170":"noin 1170","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1162":"1162","1140":"1140","after 27 September 1223":"27. syyskuut